{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477077"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:56:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:56:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14174"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14174"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.38,0.46,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6857"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54227"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6857"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14174"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39704"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2990"},{"type":"tags","id":"7894"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15625"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15626"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15627"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54227","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54227"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-month-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parents for a routine check-up. She was born at term with no complications and has been developing normally. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her immunisations are up to date. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A flat, pink-red birthmark is noted on the right side of her face, involving her forehead, upper eyelid, and cheek (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perform brain MRI","Reassure parents and review in six months","Refer for ophthalmology and neurology assessment","Refer for laser therapy","Start topical sirolimus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe description of a flat, pink-red birthmark on the face is consistent with a port wine stain, which is a congenital capillary malformation. The location of this port wine stain, involving the forehead and upper eyelid, corresponds to the distribution of the ophthalmic division (V1) of the trigeminal nerve. This distribution raises concern for Sturge-Weber syndrome, a neurocutaneous disorder associated with neurological and ophthalmological complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring for ophthalmology and neurology assessment\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. Early evaluation is crucial to screen for associated complications, particularly glaucoma and neurological issues such as seizures or developmental delays. Ophthalmology assessment can detect and monitor for glaucoma, which occurs in up to 70% of patients with Sturge-Weber syndrome. Neurological assessment can evaluate for potential intracranial involvement and guide further investigations or management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassuring parents and reviewing in six months\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate given the potential for serious complications associated with port wine stains in this distribution. Early intervention and monitoring are essential for optimal outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring for laser therapy\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered for cosmetic reasons, but it is not the priority at this stage. Management of potential systemic complications takes precedence over cosmetic concerns in infancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforming a brain MRI\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary, but this decision should be made by a neurologist after clinical assessment. Not all patients with facial port wine stains require neuroimaging, and the timing and type of imaging should be determined by a specialist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting topical sirolimus\u003C/strong\u003E is not a standard first-line treatment for port wine stains. While some studies have shown promise for topical sirolimus in certain vascular anomalies, its use in port wine stains is still investigational and should not be initiated without specialist consultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the priority in managing a patient with a port wine stain in the V1 distribution is to screen for associated complications of Sturge-Weber syndrome. Early detection and management of glaucoma and neurological issues can significantly improve outcomes for these patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Port wine stains are congenital capillary malformations that persist throughout life and may darken or thicken over time.","Sturge-Weber syndrome should be suspected in patients with port wine stains involving the ophthalmic division of the trigeminal nerve.","Early referral for ophthalmology and neurology assessment is crucial in patients with port wine stains in the V1 distribution to screen for glaucoma and neurological complications."],"references":["S\u00e1nchez-Espino LF, Ivars M, Anto\u00f1anzas J, Baselga E. Sturge-Weber Syndrome: A Review of Pathophysiology, Genetics, Clinical Features, and Current Management Approache. Appl Clin Genet. 2023 Apr 24;16:63-81. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37124240/","Image: Gellis S, Feingold M. Atlas of mental retardation syndromes; visual diagnosis of facies and physical findings. 1968. Available at: UploadWizard [online]. Available at: https://wellcomecollection.org/works/mjggc8pq"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39704"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14174"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21021"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21021"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bd34VLdw0KGSglqpjQDovM2TTLzk6q.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bd34VLdw0KGSglqpjQDovM2TTLzk6q.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":864}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39704"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-01T16:35:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-01T16:35:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6857"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54227"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology